500|$|Ionic {{compounds}} {{have long}} had {{a wide variety of}} uses and applications. Many minerals are ionic. Humans have processed common salt (sodium chloride) for over 8000 years, using it first as a food seasoning and preservative, and now also in manufacturing, agriculture, water conditioning, for de-icing roads, and many other uses. Many ionic compounds are so widely used in society that they go by common names unrelated to their chemical identity. Examples of this include borax, calomel, milk of magnesia, muriatic acid, oil of <b>vitriol,</b> saltpeter, and slaked lime. General Chemistry Virtual Textbook|accessdate=14 January 2016|date=2014}} ...|$|E
